1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,940
 So now we're gonna talk about data validation.

2
00:00:01,940 --> 00:00:04,960
 Data validation is what happens when you hit the submit button

3
00:00:04,960 --> 00:00:08,060
 and then that data is sent to the server.

4
00:00:08,060 --> 00:00:10,460
 And what the server does is it checks that post data

5
00:00:10,460 --> 00:00:14,600
 that it's getting to see if it's proper according to its rules.

6
00:00:14,600 --> 00:00:16,600
 So if you go back to this picture I showed you

7
00:00:16,600 --> 00:00:20,020
 in the create form, the part we're talking about now

8
00:00:20,020 --> 00:00:22,500
 is really this part right here.

9
00:00:22,500 --> 00:00:24,560
 Where the user has entered their data,

10
00:00:24,560 --> 00:00:26,200
 they've hit the submit button,

11
00:00:26,200 --> 00:00:28,900
 and we in the server are going to look at that data.

12
00:00:28,900 --> 00:00:31,660
 And then we are going to decide if it's an error,

13
00:00:31,660 --> 00:00:34,660
 send back a form, or store the data,

14
00:00:34,660 --> 00:00:36,620
 and we're actually sort of just have a comment

15
00:00:36,620 --> 00:00:38,740
 say store the data, and then go to the success.

16
00:00:38,740 --> 00:00:41,520
 So we're really looking at this part right here

17
00:00:41,520 --> 00:00:43,900
 of receiving and validating the data

18
00:00:43,900 --> 00:00:46,580
 and then taking all those actions, okay?

19
00:00:46,580 --> 00:00:52,740
 So the idea of data errors is you're typing in a form

20
00:00:52,740 --> 00:00:54,740
 and you forget your zip code.

21
00:00:54,740 --> 00:00:57,260
 And you hit the button and a little red box pops up

22
00:00:57,260 --> 00:00:59,460
 and says zip code is required.

23
00:00:59,460 --> 00:01:02,060
 Now you can also tell the fields in the browser

24
00:01:02,060 --> 00:01:03,620
 that they're required so that the browser

25
00:01:03,620 --> 00:01:05,080
 won't even send the data.

26
00:01:05,080 --> 00:01:08,000
 That's different and not all browsers do that.

27
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,780
 So you still have to check if you really want the zip code.

28
00:01:10,780 --> 00:01:14,280
 You've got to check to make sure the zip code is there.

29
00:01:14,280 --> 00:01:16,980
 Now in this one I made it just to generate errors.

30
00:01:16,980 --> 00:01:21,740
 I made a validator on that form if you recall,

31
00:01:21,740 --> 00:01:23,740
 that said that all the titles have to be

32
00:01:23,740 --> 00:01:25,060
 at least two characters.

33
00:01:25,060 --> 00:01:25,940
 And here's a little message.

34
00:01:25,940 --> 00:01:27,200
 Please enter two or more characters

35
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:28,380
 if that's not true.

36
00:01:28,380 --> 00:01:32,020
 'Cause otherwise the fact that it's not a string

37
00:01:32,020 --> 00:01:34,380
 or a number or whatever because the browser

38
00:01:34,380 --> 00:01:35,620
 is a little too smart for us.

39
00:01:35,620 --> 00:01:37,860
 So I had to come up with a validator

40
00:01:37,860 --> 00:01:41,080
 that would fail in the server and not fail in the browser.

41
00:01:41,080 --> 00:01:43,720
 You still need to validate data in the server.

42
00:01:43,720 --> 00:01:47,820
 So you type some stuff in.

43
00:01:47,820 --> 00:01:49,460
 You make a mistake, like in this case,

44
00:01:49,460 --> 00:01:50,900
 the title was only one letter.

45
00:01:50,900 --> 00:01:53,700
 I hit the submit button and now what I want to see

46
00:01:53,700 --> 00:01:56,580
 is a thing that tells me what the errors are

47
00:01:56,580 --> 00:01:58,820
 and gives me a chance to fix it,

48
00:01:58,820 --> 00:02:02,180
 including putting the old data that I just posted, right?

49
00:02:02,180 --> 00:02:04,460
 So it gives me my post data back.

50
00:02:04,460 --> 00:02:08,160
 And then I get a chance to resubmit.

51
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:14,040
 So again, here's the data form

52
00:02:14,040 --> 00:02:17,380
 and the validator there, it's a min length validator.

53
00:02:17,380 --> 00:02:18,820
 If you go look at the documentation,

54
00:02:18,820 --> 00:02:21,380
 there's a jillion validators.

55
00:02:21,380 --> 00:02:24,000
 This was really simple and it fits on a slide.

56
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:26,300
 So basically in addition to whatever,

57
00:02:26,300 --> 00:02:27,940
 the fact that it's gotta be a character field,

58
00:02:27,940 --> 00:02:30,380
 I want it to be at least two characters.

59
00:02:30,380 --> 00:02:34,100
 And that's not a crazy validator to have

60
00:02:34,100 --> 00:02:36,900
 because you might have a post that says,

61
00:02:36,900 --> 00:02:38,820
 look, you're not gonna have a title of one character

62
00:02:38,820 --> 00:02:41,180
 when you're doing a blog post or something like that, right?

63
00:02:41,180 --> 00:02:44,180
 You might say, look, at least five characters.

64
00:02:44,180 --> 00:02:47,020
 So now we're gonna walk through that process.

65
00:02:47,020 --> 00:02:50,080
 And so if you take a look at this code from the form,

66
00:02:50,080 --> 00:02:53,260
 in comes a get request.

67
00:02:53,260 --> 00:02:56,340
 And that get request is gonna show up with some old data.

68
00:02:56,340 --> 00:02:59,820
 It's going to create the form with the initial settings.

69
00:02:59,820 --> 00:03:01,140
 It's gonna build a context

70
00:03:01,140 --> 00:03:03,420
 that it's gonna pass into the render,

71
00:03:03,420 --> 00:03:05,740
 same render form that just makes the thing

72
00:03:05,740 --> 00:03:09,220
 with the table tags and CSRF and form post.

73
00:03:09,220 --> 00:03:11,900
 And so at this point, we are a get request,

74
00:03:11,900 --> 00:03:13,300
 we are returning a 200,

75
00:03:13,300 --> 00:03:17,100
 which is returning the HTML for that page, right?

76
00:03:17,100 --> 00:03:19,800
 So that's the first part of it.

77
00:03:19,800 --> 00:03:23,880
 And that is in the edit process, get the old data,

78
00:03:23,880 --> 00:03:27,380
 show it to the user and give the user an opportunity

79
00:03:27,380 --> 00:03:28,980
 to change the data.

80
00:03:28,980 --> 00:03:31,780
 So now we change the data, right?

81
00:03:31,780 --> 00:03:34,780
 And let's just say we didn't make any mistakes,

82
00:03:34,780 --> 00:03:36,980
 you changed a few numbers, you hit the post,

83
00:03:36,980 --> 00:03:38,420
 which gathers up all this stuff

84
00:03:38,420 --> 00:03:41,500
 and sends it as a post request to the server.

85
00:03:41,500 --> 00:03:43,860
 So then what happens is it comes into the post method,

86
00:03:43,860 --> 00:03:48,220
 see how these class based views are so dang pretty, right?

87
00:03:48,220 --> 00:03:49,060
 So pretty.

88
00:03:50,580 --> 00:03:53,300
 And it comes, and so request post read all that data

89
00:03:53,300 --> 00:03:55,740
 coming from the form comes into request post.

90
00:03:55,740 --> 00:03:57,780
 And you just construct the basic form and say,

91
00:03:57,780 --> 00:04:01,780
 hey, basic form, your old data is from the post.

92
00:04:01,780 --> 00:04:04,740
 And all the fields are named the right way

93
00:04:04,740 --> 00:04:05,880
 and the key value pairs.

94
00:04:05,880 --> 00:04:08,180
 I mean, this is basically a dictionary,

95
00:04:08,180 --> 00:04:11,500
 but the form made the key value pairs,

96
00:04:11,500 --> 00:04:14,060
 it knew what names to name all the forms,

97
00:04:14,060 --> 00:04:15,180
 so it named them.

98
00:04:15,180 --> 00:04:16,940
 And so it's not surprising,

99
00:04:16,940 --> 00:04:20,060
 it knows exactly what to expect in there, right?

100
00:04:20,060 --> 00:04:22,340
 And so it takes a look at the post data

101
00:04:22,340 --> 00:04:26,040
 and then it constructs us a form object, right?

102
00:04:26,040 --> 00:04:29,820
 It constructs us a form object and basically says,

103
00:04:29,820 --> 00:04:33,360
 if there was a validation failure,

104
00:04:33,360 --> 00:04:37,520
 if not form is valid, then we're gonna do one thing.

105
00:04:37,520 --> 00:04:40,620
 But in this case, I didn't make any changes,

106
00:04:40,620 --> 00:04:42,940
 so form is valid, so it drops down.

107
00:04:42,940 --> 00:04:44,740
 This is where we would normally store the data

108
00:04:44,740 --> 00:04:45,580
 off to the model.

109
00:04:45,580 --> 00:04:48,260
 So I'm keeping this really simple.

110
00:04:48,260 --> 00:04:52,560
 And then I'm gonna redirect with a 302 to form success.

111
00:04:52,560 --> 00:04:55,280
 The other thing I might do is put a message in the session

112
00:04:55,280 --> 00:04:57,820
 so that the message makes it into here,

113
00:04:57,820 --> 00:05:00,200
 but I'm keeping it simple.

114
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:01,640
 And the browser immediately comes back

115
00:05:01,640 --> 00:05:04,380
 and does a get to /form/success,

116
00:05:04,380 --> 00:05:06,580
 and then I return, thank you very much.

117
00:05:06,580 --> 00:05:08,160
 I might have pulled a message out,

118
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:09,980
 as we've seen in an example,

119
00:05:09,980 --> 00:05:13,840
 where I, from the post method to the next get,

120
00:05:13,840 --> 00:05:16,600
 I drop a flash message into something,

121
00:05:16,600 --> 00:05:18,160
 but there's better ways to do that,

122
00:05:18,160 --> 00:05:22,720
 and I'll show you that in an upcoming lecture series.

123
00:05:22,720 --> 00:05:26,760
 And so that's the success flow, and it works great.

124
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:29,320
 Now, let's take a look at what goes wrong.

125
00:05:29,320 --> 00:05:31,920
 So in this case, I've got my form,

126
00:05:31,920 --> 00:05:34,460
 I put in the wrong kind of title, it's too short.

127
00:05:34,460 --> 00:05:36,640
 I send a post, it gathers up all this data,

128
00:05:36,640 --> 00:05:38,200
 sends it along with the post.

129
00:05:38,200 --> 00:05:40,560
 That comes in in request.post.

130
00:05:40,560 --> 00:05:43,800
 And so now, the form comes back,

131
00:05:43,800 --> 00:05:47,420
 and now, form is valid as false,

132
00:05:47,420 --> 00:05:50,020
 because I've violated a rule.

133
00:05:50,020 --> 00:05:53,520
 Now the interesting thing is, in this form object,

134
00:05:53,520 --> 00:05:57,260
 is not only the old data, but also all the error messages,

135
00:05:57,260 --> 00:06:01,400
 because at this moment, it has constructed a form object,

136
00:06:01,400 --> 00:06:05,760
 and part of the form object is error messages, okay?

137
00:06:05,760 --> 00:06:09,400
 So, if it's not valid,

138
00:06:09,400 --> 00:06:12,800
 let's make a little context, okay?

139
00:06:12,800 --> 00:06:16,800
 Let's make a little context, and pass that in,

140
00:06:16,800 --> 00:06:21,980
 and then out it comes, and at that point,

141
00:06:21,980 --> 00:06:27,720
 that form as table is gonna print out all of this stuff,

142
00:06:27,720 --> 00:06:29,860
 all those error messages come back.

143
00:06:29,860 --> 00:06:31,020
 So I render it back.

144
00:06:31,020 --> 00:06:34,120
 Now, I render it back, and then of course,

145
00:06:34,120 --> 00:06:36,920
 you can submit it and maybe get to a success.

146
00:06:36,920 --> 00:06:40,280
 Now there is one sort of interesting question about this page,

147
00:06:40,280 --> 00:06:44,440
 which I have asked a Stack Overflow question about,

148
00:06:44,440 --> 00:06:49,240
 and I'm not sure I'm ecstatically happy about it,

149
00:06:49,240 --> 00:06:52,040
 and that is, this pattern is exactly

150
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:53,360
 how Django wants you to write it.

151
00:06:53,360 --> 00:06:56,320
 It wants you to write this, and if you'll notice,

152
00:06:56,320 --> 00:06:58,920
 I'm doing something I told you not to do.

153
00:06:58,920 --> 00:07:00,840
 Django is telling me to do something

154
00:07:00,840 --> 00:07:02,800
 that I don't wanna do, and that is,

155
00:07:02,800 --> 00:07:06,560
 return a 200 at the result of a post.

156
00:07:06,560 --> 00:07:08,920
 So you'll, I got a post.

157
00:07:08,920 --> 00:07:12,320
 Now the key thing is, the thing that everyone will agree on

158
00:07:12,320 --> 00:07:16,200
 is once you store data, you have to return a redirect.

159
00:07:16,200 --> 00:07:20,040
 And so the Django people who've done this for years,

160
00:07:20,040 --> 00:07:24,640
 they consider it okay to return the 200 on a page

161
00:07:24,640 --> 00:07:27,680
 after a post if no data was changed.

162
00:07:27,680 --> 00:07:30,400
 Now the problem is, if you hit refresh on this,

163
00:07:30,400 --> 00:07:32,560
 you're gonna get the weird funky message.

164
00:07:32,560 --> 00:07:34,680
 But this is how Django works.

165
00:07:34,680 --> 00:07:37,680
 And so, I don't know what to tell you.

166
00:07:37,680 --> 00:07:40,400
 I can write my forms differently.

167
00:07:40,400 --> 00:07:43,120
 It's a few more lines of code in here, and I've written that,

168
00:07:43,120 --> 00:07:46,320
 and I've made it so that I pass the error message

169
00:07:46,320 --> 00:07:48,600
 and I serialize the form and put it in the session

170
00:07:48,600 --> 00:07:49,480
 and do something.

171
00:07:49,480 --> 00:07:53,160
 But I'm not gonna fight City Hall on that one.

172
00:07:53,160 --> 00:07:55,760
 I'm just gonna say, if Django thinks it's fine,

173
00:07:55,760 --> 00:07:59,200
 the thing we do agree on is,

174
00:07:59,200 --> 00:08:01,280
 if you're gonna return a 200,

175
00:08:01,280 --> 00:08:03,520
 don't return a 200 after you've saved data,

176
00:08:03,520 --> 00:08:05,680
 'cause then you'll double save the data.

177
00:08:05,680 --> 00:08:07,840
 Like, you'll double commit a transaction,

178
00:08:07,840 --> 00:08:10,040
 you'll do a transfer, you'll double order,

179
00:08:10,040 --> 00:08:11,160
 you'll do whatever.

180
00:08:11,160 --> 00:08:14,040
 But in this case, all we did is looked at the data,

181
00:08:14,040 --> 00:08:16,360
 came back, and then sent back an error message.

182
00:08:16,360 --> 00:08:20,840
 So, you can look at the stack overflow

183
00:08:20,840 --> 00:08:22,960
 where I sort of argue for a little bit.

184
00:08:22,960 --> 00:08:26,400
 So, this has been a long lecture series.

185
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:29,080
 We talked about HTML, we talked about HTTP,

186
00:08:29,080 --> 00:08:31,520
 how get and post are different ways of doing it.

187
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:34,160
 We've talked about the idea of you can't,

188
00:08:34,160 --> 00:08:35,960
 how to fix the refresh.

189
00:08:35,960 --> 00:08:40,960
 We talked about cross site request forgery, CSRF,

190
00:08:40,960 --> 00:08:44,600
 and how Django handles CSRF.

191
00:08:44,600 --> 00:08:45,680
 And then toward the end here,

192
00:08:45,680 --> 00:08:48,040
 we've talked about how to define forms in Django

193
00:08:48,040 --> 00:08:51,320
 to sort of outsource all that HTML generation

194
00:08:51,320 --> 00:08:53,040
 and how we do validation.

195
00:08:53,040 --> 00:08:55,200
 Now, there's much more to learn on this

196
00:08:55,200 --> 00:08:59,080
 and we're going to learn more of the features of form objects

197
00:08:59,080 --> 00:09:02,400
 as we go forward and build increasingly complex applications.

198
00:09:02,400 --> 00:09:04,980
 (upbeat music)

